Civil Right Data Collection

https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/data

  • CRDC 2017-18 is a cross-sectional survey that collects data on key education and civil rights issues in the nation's public schools, which include student enrollment and educational programs and services, disaggregated by race/ethnicity, sex, limited English proficiency, and disability. LEAs submit administrative records about schools in the district. CRDC 2017-18 is a universe survey.
  • Codebook and Definitions: https://civilrightsdata.ed.gov/assets/downloads/2021-2220List20Definitions.pdf

Characterizing the Data

  1. Create main dataset with all features necessary (all features are other .csv files, concat by school ID)

# Preliminary EDA: Seeing Demographic difference in all students transferred to Alternative Schools by Discipline

# Transfers

transfers_df = pd.read_csv(
     "/Users/joyamelvin/Desktop/Data_Science_II/Last_Girls_Standing_Repo/2017-18_CRDC_data/2017-18 Public-Use Files/Data/SCH/CRDC/CSV/Transfers.csv",
    encoding='windows-1252'
)

transfer_vars = [
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_BL_F',
'SCH_DISCWDIS_TFRALT_IDEA_BL_F',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_HI_M', 
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_HI_F',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_AM_M',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_AM_F',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_AS_M',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_AS_F',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_HP_M',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_HP_F',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_BL_M',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_BL_F',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_WH_M',
'SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_WH_F'
]

reserve_codes = [-3, -5, -6, -8, -9, -11]

# Validate which transfer_vars exist in the DataFrame
existing_transfer_vars = [col for col in transfer_vars if col in transfers_df.columns]

# Replace reserve codes with 0 one column at a time
for col in existing_transfer_vars:
    transfers_df[col] = pd.to_numeric(transfers_df[col], errors='coerce')  # ensure numeric
    transfers_df[col] = transfers_df[col].replace(reserve_codes, 0)

# Sum totals across all schools
transfer_totals = transfers_df[existing_transfer_vars].sum().sort_values(ascending=False)

# Prepare for plotting
transfer_df = transfer_totals.reset_index()
transfer_df.columns = ['Group', 'Total Transferred']

transfer_df['Group'] = transfer_df['Group'].str.replace('SCH_DISCWODIS_TFRALT_', '').str.replace('_', ' ')

# Labels
label_map = {
    'BL M': 'Black Male',
    'BL F': 'Black Female',
    'WH M': 'White Male',
    'WH F': 'White Female',
    'HI M': 'Hispanic Male',
    'HI F': 'Hispanic Female',
    'AM M': 'American Indian Male',
    'AM F': 'American Indian Female',
    'AS M': 'Asian Male',
    'AS F': 'Asian Female',
    'HP M': 'Pacific Islander Male',
    'HP F': 'Pacific Islander Female',
    'SCH DISCWDIS TFRALT IDEA BL F': 'Black Female (w/Disability)'
}

# Apply label mapping
transfer_df['Group'] = transfer_df['Group'].replace(label_map)


# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(data=transfer_df, x='Total Transferred', y='Group', palette='Spectral')
plt.title('2017-18 CRDC Students Transferred to Alternative Schools by Race and Gender')
plt.xlabel('Number of Students Transferred')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("intro_eda.png", dpi=300)
plt.show()

# Visualize 
reserve_codes = [-3, -5, -6, -8, -9, -11]

# Initialize dictionary to hold totals per code
code_totals = {code: 0 for code in reserve_codes}

for col in target_df.columns:
    try:
        col_numeric = pd.to_numeric(target_df[col], errors='coerce')
        for code in reserve_codes:
            code_totals[code] += (col_numeric == code).sum()
    except:
        continue  # skip columns that can't be coerced to numeric

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Convert to DataFrame for plotting
code_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(code_totals, orient='index', columns=['Count']).sort_values(by='Count', ascending=False)

# Plot

figsize = (8, 5)
fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
code_df.plot(kind='bar', legend=False, rot=0, color='orange', ax=ax2)
ax2.set_title('Reserve Codes for Target Indicators (School Harm)')
ax2.set_xlabel('Reserve Code')
ax2.set_ylabel('Total Count')
ax2.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('target_reserve_code_distribution.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
plt.close()

target_df.loc[:, ~target_df.columns.isin(excluded_cols)] = target_df.loc[:, ~target_df.columns.isin(excluded_cols)].apply(
    lambda col: col.mask(col.isin(codes)) if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(col) else col.replace([str(code) for code in codes], np.nan)
)

# Visualize 
reserve_codes = [-3, -5, -6, -8, -9, -11]

# Initialize dictionary to hold totals per code
code_totals = {code: 0 for code in reserve_codes}

for col in feature_df.columns:
    try:
        col_numeric = pd.to_numeric(feature_df[col], errors='coerce')
        for code in reserve_codes:
            code_totals[code] += (col_numeric == code).sum()
    except:
        continue  # skip columns that can't be coerced to numeric


# Convert to DataFrame for plotting
code_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(code_totals, orient='index', columns=['Count']).sort_values(by='Count', ascending=False)

# Plot
figsize = (8, 5)
fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize)
code_df.plot(kind='bar', legend=False, rot=0, color='orange', ax=ax1)

ax1.set_xlabel('Reserve Code')
ax1.set_ylabel('Total Count')
ax1.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Dropping all reserve codes to get full dataset

# Apply masking to all other columns
feature_df.loc[:, ~feature_df.columns.isin(excluded_cols)] = feature_df.loc[:, ~feature_df.columns.isin(excluded_cols)].apply(
    lambda col: col.mask(col.isin(codes)) if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(col) else col.replace([str(code) for code in codes], np.nan)
)

  • 60% - 95% : Aggregate into "total retention"; make a binary class
  • 25% - 50%: Mostly Arrests, suspensions, restraint, referrals, harassment, expulsion; Impute missing values as 0; likely never happened or undocumented.
  • < 25% : Impute the rest as 0
  • Drop rows empty or 0 for enrollment (does not have black girls in their school)

# --- D. Mice Imputation for Salary ---
from sklearn.experimental import enable_iterative_imputer  # Required to enable IterativeImputer
from sklearn.impute import IterativeImputer
import pandas as pd

# Define the salary columns you want to impute
salary_cols = [
    'SCH_SAL_TEACH_WFED',
    'SCH_SAL_SUP_WFED',
    'SCH_SAL_ADM_WFED',
    'SCH_SAL_TOTPERS_WFED'
]

# Optional: choose correlated predictors to improve imputation (already part of your df)
mice_features = salary_cols + [
    'SCH_FTETEACH_TOT', 
    'SCH_FTECOUNSELORS', 
    'SCH_FTESERVICES_SOC', 
    'SCH_ENR_BL_F', 
    'total_population'
]

# Subset the data
mice_data = feature_df[mice_features].copy()

# Initialize MICE imputer
mice_imputer = IterativeImputer(random_state=42, max_iter=10)

# Fit and transform
mice_imputed = mice_imputer.fit_transform(mice_data)

# Put back into DataFrame
mice_imputed_df = pd.DataFrame(mice_imputed, columns=mice_data.columns, index=mice_data.index)

# Replace the original salary columns in feature_df
feature_df[salary_cols] = mice_imputed_df[salary_cols]

#Test 
# CCP Pruning the tree 

# Train a full Decision Tree
dt_full = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)
dt_full.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get CCP Path
path = dt_full.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas = path.ccp_alphas  # List of alpha values

valid_ccp_alphas = [alpha for alpha in ccp_alphas if alpha >= 0.0]

# Train trees with different pruning strengths
pruned_trees = []
for alpha in valid_ccp_alphas:
    dt_pruned = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=alpha, class_weight='balanced')
    dt_pruned.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pruned_trees.append(dt_pruned)
In[500]:
# Best CCP_Alpha  

best_alpha = None
best_accuracy = 0

for i, alpha in enumerate(valid_ccp_alphas):
    y_pred_val = pruned_trees[i].predict(X_test)
    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_val)
    
    if acc > best_accuracy:
        best_accuracy = acc
        best_alpha = alpha

print(f"Best ccp_alpha for pruning: {best_alpha}")

Best ccp_alpha for pruning: 0.0062632086286680405

from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import numpy as np

# Define the hyperparameter distribution
rf_param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300, 400, 500],
    'max_depth': [5, 10, 15, 20, None],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],
    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2', None],
    'bootstrap': [True, False],
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy']
}

# Initialize the base RF model
rf_base = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Randomized Search CV with 50 iterations
random_search_rf = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=rf_base,
    param_distributions=rf_param_dist,
    n_iter=50,  # Try 50 random combinations
    cv=3,
    scoring='f1',
    verbose=2,
    random_state=42,
    n_jobs=-1
)

# Fit the random search
random_search_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters
print("Best parameters from RandomizedSearchCV:", random_search_rf.best_params_)

# Best estimator
best_rf = random_search_rf.best_estimator_

# Post-Tuning Assesment 
best_xgb = random_search_xgb.best_estimator_
y_pred_xgb_best = best_xgb.predict(X_test)

print("Post-Tuning Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred_xgb_best))
print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_xgb_best))

# Confusion matrix
sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_xgb_best), annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Greens')
plt.title("Tuned XG Confusion Matrix")
plt.xlabel("Predicted")
plt.ylabel("Actual")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("xgboost_confusion_matrix.png", dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

# AUC Score
y_probs_best = best_xgb.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
print(f"AUC Score: {roc_auc_score(y_test, y_probs_best):.4f}")

# get RMSE and R2
r2_xgb_best = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_xgb_best)
rmse_xgb_best = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_xgb_best))

print(f"Tuned XGB R: {r2_xgb_best:.4f}")
print(f"Tuned XGB RMSE: {rmse_xgb_best:.4f}")

# Get feature importances by gain
importance_type = 'gain'
importance_dict = best_xgb.get_booster().get_score(importance_type=importance_type)

# Convert to DataFrame
importance_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'feature': list(importance_dict.keys()),
    'importance': list(importance_dict.values())
}).sort_values(by='importance', ascending=False)

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(importance_df['feature'][:20][::-1], importance_df['importance'][:20][::-1])
plt.title(f'Top 20 Feature Importances ({importance_type})')
plt.xlabel("Importance Score")
plt.ylabel("Feature")
plt.tight_layout()
